article.headline: Virginia turnovers give North Carolina easy win
article.linkText: Tar Heels finish season perfect at home
article.story:
CHAPEL HILL, N.C. (AP) -- Ivory Latta scored 19 points, going
4-for-4 from 3-point range, and North Carolina (No. 4 ESPN/USA Today; No. 8 AP) completed a perfect
home schedule Thursday night with an 89-60 victory against Virginia.
	   Nikita Bell added 13 points, and La'Tangela Atkinson had 10 for
the Tar Heels (23-3, 11-2 Atlantic Coast Conference), who
earned their largest margin of victory against Virginia.
	   North Carolina finished 15-0 at home this season and has gone
54-4 there the past four years. The Tar Heels will conclude the
regular season Sunday at No. 2 Duke.
	   Brandi Teamer scored Virginia's first nine points but finished
with only 11. Siedah Williams scored 10 for the Cavaliers (18-9,
7-6).
	   Virginia made only 21 of 68 field-goal attempts (30.9 percent)
and committed 29 turnovers. The Cavaliers failed to make a basket
from the 6:06 mark of the first half to 13:57 of the second.
	   North Carolina stretched its lead to 34 points, 83-49, on a
layup by senior Kenya McBee with 3:16 left.
	   Latta made her first three 3-point tries and scored 13
first-half points to spark North Carolina to a 37-19 lead at the
break. The Tar Heels turned 15 turnovers into 14 points in the
first half.
